1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,630
We all understand the importance of reproducible workflows.

2
00:00:03,630 --> 00:00:07,605
Programmatic approaches towards these are an excellent starting point.

3
00:00:07,605 --> 00:00:11,190
Here are a couple of tips to keep in mind as you're going about your mingling.

4
00:00:11,190 --> 00:00:15,345
One, ensure your folder names are descriptive and consistent.

5
00:00:15,345 --> 00:00:20,250
Take a look at an example on the screen where we use the ISO date format, year,

6
00:00:20,250 --> 00:00:25,275
month, and day, and provide a description of the type of data that would be contained.

7
00:00:25,275 --> 00:00:28,800
Your use case may require a specific naming convention.

8
00:00:28,800 --> 00:00:32,750
You may also consider using hyphens or underscores instead of spaces

9
00:00:32,750 --> 00:00:37,015
in the zip file to make it easier to programmatically access your data folders.

10
00:00:37,015 --> 00:00:40,810
Two, make sure the sub-files are also named constructively.

11
00:00:40,810 --> 00:00:44,240
For example, if you're grouping data by time within the zip folder,

12
00:00:44,240 --> 00:00:48,260
use the ISO date format for those individual folders and files too.

13
00:00:48,260 --> 00:00:53,710
Three, create a clear and consistent structure of files within the zip folder.

14
00:00:53,710 --> 00:00:57,020
For example, you may group all data corresponding to

15
00:00:57,020 --> 00:01:02,420
a specific microscopy sample under a folder called 202303 Sample A,

16
00:01:02,420 --> 00:01:08,850
or group all data collected in a single day under a folder titled, with the day.

